@context: Wikipedia Comprehensive Research Marathon
@title: large_scale_navigation_and_extraction

# 🐾 WIKIPEDIA HUNT: The 50-Step Marathon
#
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FEATURES DEMONSTRATED:
#
#   Fill '...' with '...' and press Enter
#                       — Combines typing and pressing Enter in one step.
#                         The engine fills the field and then simulates
#                         an Enter keypress (equivalent to a separate
#                         PRESS ENTER step). Useful for search forms.
#
#   EXTRACT ... into {var}
#                       — Captures text into runtime variables. Multiple
#                         EXTRACTs build a variable store that persists
#                         for the entire mission. Variables can be reused
#                         in later steps with {placeholder} syntax.
#
#   SCROLL DOWN         — Scrolls the main page by one viewport height.
#                         The engine uses this before interacting with
#                         elements that may be below the fold.
#
#   Cross-page navigation
#                       — Clicking in-page links (e.g. 'Taxonomy',
#                         'Microsoft') navigates to new pages. The engine
#                         auto-waits for DOM settlement after each
#                         navigation. VERIFY after navigation confirms
#                         the expected page loaded.
#
#   Large-scale test    — 50+ actions across 7+ Wikipedia pages in a
#                         single .hunt file. Demonstrates that the engine
#                         handles long sessions without losing state or
#                         variable context.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

STEP 1: Land on Wikipedia home
    NAVIGATE to https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page
    VERIFY that 'Welcome to Wikipedia' is present.

STEP 2: Research — Pallas's cat
    # "and press Enter" at the end triggers form submission after fill.
    Fill 'Search Wikipedia' field with "Pallas's cat" and press Enter
    VERIFY that 'Otocolobus manul' is present.
    # Extract structured data from the infobox into runtime variables.
    EXTRACT the text of 'Order:' into {manul_order}
    EXTRACT the text of 'Family:' into {manul_family}
    Click on the 'Taxonomy' link
    VERIFY that 'Peter Simon Pallas' is present.
    SCROLL DOWN
    Click on the 'Characteristics' link
    VERIFY that 'rounded ears' is present.
    Click on the 'Distribution and habitat' link
    VERIFY that 'Caucasus' is present.
    SCROLL DOWN

STEP 3: Research — Software Testing
    Fill 'Search Wikipedia' field with "Software testing" and press Enter
    VERIFY that 'software quality' is present.
    Click on the 'History' link
    VERIFY that 'Glenford J. Myers' is present.
    VERIFY that 'Black-box' is present.
    SCROLL DOWN

STEP 4: Research — Selenium
    Fill 'Search Wikipedia' field with "Selenium (software)" and press Enter
    VERIFY that 'Jason Huggins' is present.
    EXTRACT the text of 'Stable release' into {selenium_release}
    EXTRACT the text of 'License' into {selenium_license}
    Click on the 'Selenium WebDriver' link
    VERIFY that 'browser automation' is present.
    SCROLL DOWN

STEP 5: Research — Playwright and Microsoft
    Fill 'Search Wikipedia' field with "Playwright (software)" and press Enter
    VERIFY that 'Microsoft' is present.
    EXTRACT the text of 'Initial release' into {playwright_release}
    EXTRACT the text of 'Repository' into {playwright_repo}
    Click on the 'Microsoft' link
    VERIFY that 'Bill Gates' is present.
    EXTRACT the text of 'Traded as' into {msft_stock}
    EXTRACT the text of 'Headquarters' into {msft_hq}
    Click on the 'History' link
    VERIFY that 'Paul Allen' is present.
    SCROLL DOWN
    Click on the 'Corporate affairs' link
    VERIFY that 'Board of directors' is present.

STEP 6: Research — Python
    Fill 'Search Wikipedia' field with "Python (programming language)" and press Enter
    VERIFY that 'Guido van Rossum' is present.
    EXTRACT the text of 'Typing discipline' into {python_typing}
    EXTRACT the text of 'OS' into {python_os}
    Click on the 'Syntax and semantics' link
    VERIFY that 'Indentation' is present.

STEP 7: Return to home
    Click on the 'Main menu' button
    Click on the 'Main page' link
    VERIFY that 'Welcome to Wikipedia' is present.
DONE.
